Restaurateur Hana Assafiri at her Moroccan Deli-cacy cafe in Brunswick. Photo: Justin McManus 

Ms Assafiri had planned to fly to New York in March to an international conference on the status of women.  

But she has decided not to go, which she says is &quot;100 per cent&quot; due to the ban and unease at how authorities might act towards her. 

&quot;They can take you without notice, they can deem you whatever; there&apos;s absolutely no process, no human rights, everything&apos;s been scaled back. It&apos;s a scary, scary ... it&apos;s a war, that&apos;s been declared on people. It&apos;s ridiculous.&quot; 

Qantas has said it will offer refunds to any passengers caught up in the immigration freeze. 

&quot;Passengers booked on Qantas for travel to the United States who use a passport from Iran, Iraq, Sudan, Somalia, Syria, Yemen, Libya have a number of options, including a change to their destination or a refund,&quot; the airline said in a statement. 

A spokesman for Jetstar, which flies to Honolulu, said no passengers were known to be affected, but the airline was &quot;finalising what we will do in the event that we do have passengers that are impacted&quot;. 

